5. Projection Queries and DTO-based Results

Why use projections?
Sometimes you don’t need the whole entity—just a few fields.
Projections let you fetch only what you need, making queries faster and reducing data
transfer.

Sometimes you want to fetch only specific fields, not the whole entity. This is called a
projection.

a. Interface-based Projection

How does it work?
You create an interface with getter methods for the fields you want. Spring Data JPA
will automatically map the query result to this interface.

Ex:

public interface UserNameOnly {
    String getName();
}

List<UserNameOnly> findByStatus(Status status);

Info:
This will return a list of objects with only the name field populated.
When to use: For simple projections (few fields, no logic).
Returns only the name field for each user.

b. DTO-based Projection

What is a DTO?
DTO stands for Data Transfer Object—a simple class used to carry data, often between
layers of an application.

How does it work?
You create a class with a constructor for the fields you want, then use a JPQL constructor
expression.

Ex:

Create a DTO (Data Transfer Object):

public class UserDTO {
    private String name;
    private String email;
    public UserDTO(String name, String email) {
        this.name = name;
        this.email = email;
    }
    // getters
}

Use a constructor expression in JPQL:

@Query("SELECT new com.example.UserDTO(u.name, u.email) FROM User u WHERE u.status = :status")
List<UserDTO> findUserDTOByStatus(@Param("status") Status status);

Info:
This returns a list of UserDTO objects, each containing only name and email.
When to use: For more complex projections, or when you need to add logic or combine fields.

Feature	                     When to Use	                   Example

Query Derivation	        Simple queries	                   findByEmail(String email)
@Query (JPQL)	            Complex, object-oriented queries   JPQL with entity fields
@Query (Native SQL)	        DB-specific or legacy queries	   SQL with table/column names
Interface Projection	    Simple, few fields	               UserNameOnly interface
DTO Projection	            Custom data shapes, logic,         UserDTO class
                            multiple fields